05973nam a22009375i 9780674061330DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2011    mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740613307 a10.4159/harvard.97806740613302doi  a(DE-B1597)178259  a(OCoLC)754715003  a(OCoLC)979746511  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKKP206b.T48 2011eb 7aHIS0100102bisacsh04a364.1 88094382221 aTeter, Magda, eauthor.10aSinners on Trial :bJews and Sacrilege after the Reformation /cMagda Teter. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource :b15 halftones, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00t Frontmatter -- tContents -- tMap -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Meaning of the Sacred -- t2. Stealing Sacred Objects -- t3. Prosecuting Sins, Defending Faith -- t4. The Making of a Polish Jerusalem -- t5. Protestant Heresy and Charges against Jews -- t6. Christians on Trial, Jews Expelled -- t7. The Struggle for Power and Authority -- t8. Justice and the Politics of Crime -- tGlossary -- tAbbreviations -- tNote on Names and Terminology -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn post-Reformation Poland-the largest state in Europe and home to the largest Jewish population in the world-the Catholic Church suffered profound anxiety about its power after the Protestant threat. Magda Teter reveals how criminal law became a key tool in the manipulation of the meaning of the sacred and in the effort to legitimize Church authority. The mishandling of sacred symbols was transformed from a sin that could be absolved into a crime that resulted in harsh sentences of mutilation, hanging, decapitation, and, principally, burning at the stake.Teter casts new light on the most infamous type of sacrilege, the accusation against Jews for desecrating the eucharistic wafer. These sacrilege trials were part of a broader struggle over the meaning of the sacred and of sacred space at a time of religious and political uncertainty, with the eucharist at its center. But host desecration-defined in the law as sacrilege-went beyond anti-Jewish hatred to reflect Catholic-Protestant conflict, changing conditions of ecclesiastic authority and jurisdiction, and competition in the economic marketplace.Recounting dramatic stories of torture, trial, and punishment, this is the first book to consider the sacrilege accusations of the early modern period within the broader context of politics and common crime. Teter draws on previously unexamined trial records to bring out the real-life relationships among Catholics, Jews, and Protestants and challenges the commonly held view that following the Reformation, Poland was a "state without stakes"-uniquely a country without religious persecution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aCounter-ReformationzPoland. 0aJewsxLegal status, laws, etc.zPolandxHistory. 0aReligious minoritiesxLegal status, laws, etc.zPolandxHistory. 0aSacrilegezPolandxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2011z9783110261189oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2011z978311026123308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET PHILOSOPHIE UND GESCHICHTE 2011z9783110261257oZDB-23-DGE08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP Complete eBook Package 2011-2014z978311037488908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package 2011z978311037492608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z9783110442205